{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019WSsjCT2udA7iDNTjg4Pnq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the details. Let me create the Kubernetes manifests for a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster:\n\n1. A ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. A headless Service for inter-node communication (transport port 9300)\n3. A ClusterIP Service named `es-http` for HTTPS access (port 9200)\n4. A StatefulSet with 3 replicas\n5. Optionally a PodDisruptionBudget\n\nKey considerations for Elasticsearch 8.x:\n- By default, Elasticsearch 8.x has security enabled (HTTPS + authentication)\n- I need to configure both HTTP and transport layer TLS using the existing secret\n- The cluster requires `discovery.seed_hosts` and `cluster.initial_master_nodes` settings for proper node discovery\n- Transport SSL is mandatory in 8.x for inter-node communication, and I can reuse the same TLS certificates for both HTTP and transport layers as long as the certificate covers the pod DNS names\n- I'm weighing whether to use the same cert for both layers, disable transport SSL entirely (which requires careful configuration), or generate separate transport certificates\n- One practical option is to set the transport SSL verification mode to accept any certificate, then use the existing TLS secret for both HTTP and transport\n\nWriting config options... Writing the Elasticsearch config... I need to handle `vm.max_map_count` configuration, and the most reliable way is using a privileged init container that runs a sysctl command to set the value to 262144. I'll also need to set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable for Elasticsearch authentication, then consolidate all the manifests into a single file.\n\nFor the StatefulSet, I'm using the pod's metadata name as the node name by referencing it through fieldRef, which Elasticsearch will use to identify each node in the cluster. I can either set this in the ConfigMap with variable interpolation or pass it directly as an environment variable that Elasticsearch recognizes.\n\nFor storage, I'm deciding between emptyDir for simplicity in a benchmark scenario versus volumeClaimTemplates for persistent storage. Since we're testing reads and writes without knowing if a StorageClass is available, emptyDir makes sense. I also need to constrain the Java heap size via ES_JAVA_OPTS since Elasticsearch 8.x tries to claim a lot of memory by default.\n\nWriting the manifest structure... Now I'm setting up the Kubernetes services and StatefulSet for the Elasticsearch cluster—creating a headless service for inter-node communication on port 9300, an HTTP service for client access on port 9200, and configuring a StatefulSet with three replicas...\n\nConfiguring the Elasticsearch container...\n\nI'm setting up the port mappings for the HTTP and transport protocols, then mounting the configuration file, TLS certificates, and persistent data volume. The container has memory and CPU requests and limits defined, and I'm using a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration and a Secret for the TLS certificates. Now I need to think about the data directory permissions since Elasticsearch runs as a specific user.\n\nI should add a securityContext to handle the user permissions properly, and for this test environment, emptyDir works fine for storage. I'm also adding a PodDisruptionBudget to ensure at least two pods remain available during disruptions. Let me refine the security context since the official Elasticsearch 8.x image runs as the elasticsearch user with UID 1000, and the data directory needs to be writable by that user.\n\nFor the cluster configuration, `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is only needed for initial bootstrap, so it's safe to leave in place. The default node roles in ES 8.x make all nodes master-eligible and data nodes, which works fine for a 3-node cluster. The headless service will create the proper DNS entries for discovery, so I need to make sure the discovery configuration points to those entries correctly.\n\nI should mount the ConfigMap at the elasticsearch config directory using `subPath` to replace just the elasticsearch.yml file without overwriting other configs. For this benchmark scenario, I'll use `emptyDir` for storage instead of requiring PersistentVolumes. One concern is whether the certificate I'm using has the right SANs for both HTTP and transport layer SSL, since I'm reusing the same cert/key pair for both. I'm reconsidering whether disabling transport SSL actually works in ES 8.x. The documentation states that security is enabled by default and TLS is required for the transport layer, so setting `xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false` might not be viable and could cause startup failures.\n\nThe single-node exception won't help since we need a 3-node cluster. Instead, I should configure transport SSL with the CA certificate and use `verification_mode: certificate` to verify the cert is signed by the CA without requiring exact hostname matching in the SANs.\n\nActually, `verification_mode: none` is simpler and will definitely work, so let me go with that approach. Now I need to finalize the manifest and apply it, but first I should handle the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable that ES 8.x requires when security is enabled.\n\nFor the StatefulSet, I also need to set `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to match the pod names like `elasticsearch-0,elasticsearch-1,elasticsearch-2`, and configure `node.name` to use the pod name via environment variable interpolation with the `${NODE_NAME}` syntax in the elasticsearch.yml file.\n\nI should add readiness and liveness probes to ensure the cluster reaches a healthy state. The readiness probe will check the cluster health endpoint via HTTPS with certificate validation and basic auth, waiting for either green or yellow status before marking the pod as ready. Writing readiness probe...\n\nFor resource limits, I'm thinking 512MB heap is reasonable for testing on a kind cluster, with a 1GB memory limit to give some breathing room.\n\nI should clarify that `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` is the standard way to set the superuser password—there's no separate `ELASTIC_USERNAME` env var since it always defaults to the `elastic` user. The keystore isn't necessary here since we're using environment variables.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the full manifest, and I'll combine everything into a single YAML file with multiple documents separated by `---` for easier kubectl application.\n\nWriting the manifest... Writing Kubernetes manifests... Configuring the readiness probe to check cluster health status, then setting up volume mounts for the configuration file, TLS certificates, and persistent data storage, along with resource requests and limits for memory and CPU allocation.\n\nI'm verifying that the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable is properly supported in ES 8.x Docker images for setting the elastic user's password on first startup. I should also consider adding memory locking configuration with the appropriate security context capabilities to prevent swapping, which Elasticsearch recommends for production deployments.\n\nFor the data directory ownership, I need to set the fsGroup to 1000 so the elasticsearch group has the right permissions. And on the headless service, `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` is crucial—it ensures pods can discover each other during startup even before they're fully ready. Let me write out the manifest and apply it to see if everything works as expected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":293,"cache_read_input_tokens":29260,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":293},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8db3a55-0d34-47f9-a2a1-261f430454c3","uuid":"ca545e26-b469-40e5-b96f-e7e144b2a0f2","request_id":"req_011CcLZnasDn7y5mqQtsWgA5"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019WSsjCT2udA7iDNTjg4Pnq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll create and apply the manifests for a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":293,"cache_read_input_tokens":29260,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":293},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8db3a55-0d34-47f9-a2a1-261f430454c3","uuid":"ab88c868-85d3-46e6-b968-7a51ff8acce9","request_id":"req_011CcLZnasDn7y5mqQtsWgA5"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019WSsjCT2udA7iDNTjg4Pnq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WmpYEwv888mUHgmzCrXnYX","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/mydata/karma/runs/error-prone-rererun/elasticsearch-password-ingress-audit-change-plan-20260623_171247/stages/stage_01/es-cluster.yaml","content":"---\napiVersion: v1\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  name: elasticsearch-config\n  namespace: elasticsearch\ndata:\n  elasticsearch.yml: |\n    cluster.name: karma-es\n    node.name: ${NODE_NAME}\n    network.host: 0.0.0.0\n    discovery.seed_hosts: elasticsearch-headless\n    cluster.initial_master_nodes: elasticsearch-0,elasticsearch-1,elasticsearch-2\n    xpack.security.enabled: \"true\"\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: \"true\"\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate_authorities: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: \"true\"\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.verification_mode: none\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\n---\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Service\nmetadata:\n  name: elasticsearch-headless\n  namespace: elasticsearch\n  labels:\n    app: elasticsearch\nspec:\n  clusterIP: None\n  publishNotReadyAddresses: true\n  selector:\n    app: elasticsearch\n  ports:\n  - name: https\n    port: 9200\n    protocol: TCP\n  - name: transport\n    port: 9300\n    protocol: TCP\n---\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Service\nmetadata:\n  name: es-http\n  namespace: elasticsearch\n  labels:\n    app: elasticsearch\nspec:\n  selector:\n    app: elasticsearch\n  ports:\n  - name: https\n    port: 9200\n    targetPort: 9200\n    protocol: TCP\n---\napiVersion: policy/v1\nkind: PodDisruptionBudget\nmetadata:\n  name: elasticsearch-pdb\n  namespace: elasticsearch\nspec:\n  minAvailable: 2\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: elasticsearch\n---\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: StatefulSet\nmetadata:\n  name: elasticsearch\n  namespace: elasticsearch\nspec:\n  serviceName: elasticsearch-headless\n  replicas: 3\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: elasticsearch\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: elasticsearch\n    spec:\n      initContainers:\n      - name: sysctl\n        image: busybox:1.36\n        command: [\"sysctl\", \"-w\", \"vm.max_map_count=262144\"]\n        securityContext:\n          privileged: true\n      securityContext:\n        fsGroup: 1000\n      containers:\n      - name: elasticsearch\n        image: docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:8.11.1\n        env:\n        - name: NODE_NAME\n          valueFrom:\n            fieldRef:\n              fieldPath: metadata.name\n        - name: ELASTIC_PASSWORD\n          valueFrom:\n            secretKeyRef:\n              name: elastic-password\n              key: password\n        - name: ES_JAVA_OPTS\n          value: \"-Xms512m -Xmx512m\"\n        ports:\n        - containerPort: 9200\n          name: https\n          protocol: TCP\n        - containerPort: 9300\n          name: transport\n          protocol: TCP\n        readinessProbe:\n          exec:\n            command:\n            - bash\n            - -c\n            - |\n              curl -s -k -u \"elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\" \\\n                https://localhost:9200/_cluster/health?local=true \\\n                | grep -qE '\"status\":\"(green|yellow)\"'\n          initialDelaySeconds: 60\n          periodSeconds: 10\n          timeoutSeconds: 10\n          failureThreshold: 6\n        resources:\n          requests:\n            memory: \"1Gi\"\n            cpu: \"500m\"\n          limits:\n            memory: \"1Gi\"\n        volumeMounts:\n        - name: config\n          mountPath: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.yml\n          subPath: elasticsearch.yml\n        - name: tls\n          mountPath: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs\n          readOnly: true\n        - name: data\n          mountPath: /usr/share/elasticsearch/data\n      volumes:\n      - name: config\n        configMap:\n          name: elasticsearch-config\n      - name: tls\n        secret:\n          secretName: es-http-tls\n      - name: data\n        emptyDir: {}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":293,"cache_read_input_tokens":29260,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":293},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8db3a55-0d34-47f9-a2a1-261f430454c3","uuid":"eb0eb108-977e-41ea-8e2a-4e12281929fd","request_id":"req_011CcLZnasDn7y5mqQtsWgA5"}
